# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: index-tree-structures
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] In computer science, a **B-tree** is a self-balancing tree data structure that maintains sorted data and allows searches, sequential access, insertions, and deletions in logarithmic time.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] The B-tree generalizes the binary search tree, allowing nodes to have more than two children.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] By allowing more children under one node than a regular self-balancing binary search tree, the B-tree reduces the height of the tree and puts the data in fewer separate blocks.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] This is especially important for trees stored in secondary storage (e.g., disk drives), as these systems have relatively high latency and work with relatively large blocks of data, hence the B-tree's use in databases and file systems.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] This remains a major advantage when the tree is stored in memory, as modern computer systems rely heavily on CPU caches.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] Compared to reading from the cache, reading from memory after a cache miss costs significant time.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] While working at Boeing Research Labs, Rudolf Bayer and Edward M.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] McCreight invented B-trees to efficiently manage index pages for large random-access files.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] Their basic assumption was that indices would be so voluminous that only small chunks of the tree could fit in the main memory.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] Bayer and McCreight's paper *Organization and maintenance of large ordered indices* was first circulated in July 1970 and later published in *Acta Informatica*.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] Bayer and McCreight never explained what, if anything, the *B* stands for; *Boeing*, *balanced*, *between*, *broad*, *bushy*, and *Bayer* have been suggested.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] Every node, except for the root and the leaves, has at least ⌈*m*/2⌉ children.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] The root node has at least two children unless it is a leaf.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] A non-leaf node with *k* children contains *k*−1 keys.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] The keys of each non-leaf node act as separation values that divide its subtrees.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] For example, if an internal node has 3 child nodes (or subtrees), then it must have 2 keys: *a*1 and *a*2.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] All values in the leftmost subtree will be less than *a*1, all values in the middle subtree will be between *a*1 and *a*2, and all values in the rightmost subtree will be greater than *a*2.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] ) are all nodes except for leaf nodes and the root node.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] They are usually represented as an ordered set of elements and child pointers.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] −1; therefore, each internal node is at least half full.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] implies that two half-full nodes can be joined to make a legal node, and one full node can be split into two legal nodes (if there's room to push one element up into the parent).
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] These properties make it possible to delete and insert new values into a B-tree while also adjusting the tree to preserve its properties.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] The root node's number of children has the same upper limit as internal nodes but has no lower limit.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] −1 elements in the entire tree, the root will be the only node in the tree with no children at all.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] In Knuth's terminology, the "leaf" nodes are the actual data objects/chunks.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] /2-1 if they are not the root) and pointers (one for each key) to nodes carrying the data objects/chunks.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] A B-tree of depth *n*+1 can hold about *U* times as many items as a B-tree of depth *n*, but the cost of search, insert, and delete operations grows with the depth of the tree.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] As with any balanced tree, the cost grows much more slowly than the number of elements.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] Some balanced trees store values only at leaf nodes and use different kinds of nodes for leaf nodes and internal nodes.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] B-trees keep values in every node in the tree except leaf nodes.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] The literature on B-trees is not uniform in its terminology.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] Bayer and McCreight (1972), Comer (1979), and others define the **order** of a B-tree as the minimum number of keys in a non-root node.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] Folk and Zoellick point out that terminology is ambiguous because the maximum number of keys is unclear.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] An order 3 B-tree might hold a maximum of 6 keys or a maximum of 7 keys.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] Knuth (1998) avoids the problem by defining the **order** to be the maximum number of children (which is one more than the maximum number of keys).
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] Bayer and McCreight (1972) considered the leaf level to be the lowest level of keys, but Knuth considered the leaf level to be one level below the lowest keys.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] There are many possible implementation choices.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] In some designs, the leaves may hold the entire data record; in other designs, the leaves may only hold pointers to the data record.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] Those choices are not fundamental to the idea of a B-tree.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] For simplicity, most authors assume there is a fixed number of keys that fit in a node.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] The basic assumption is that the key size and node size are both fixed.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] In practice, variable-length keys may be employed.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] As with other trees, B-trees can be represented as a collection of three types of nodes: *root*, *internal* (a.k.a. interior), and *leaf*.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] To maintain the predefined range of child nodes, internal nodes may be joined or split.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] Usually, the number of keys is chosen to vary between d and $2d$ , where d is the minimum number of keys, and $d+1$ is the minimum degree or branching factor of the tree.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] The factor of 2 will guarantee that nodes can be split or combined.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] If an internal node has $2d$ keys, then adding a key to that node can be accomplished by splitting the hypothetical $2d+1$ key node into two d key nodes and moving the key that would have been in the middle to the parent node.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] Each split node has the required minimum number of keys.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] Similarly, if an internal node and its neighbor each have d keys, then a key may be deleted from the internal node by combining it with its neighbor.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] Deleting the key would make the internal node have $d-1$ keys; joining the neighbor would add d keys plus one more key brought down from the neighbor's parent.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] The result is an entirely full node of $2d$ keys.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] A B-tree is kept balanced after insertion by splitting a would-be overfilled node, of $2d+1$ keys, into two d-key siblings and inserting the mid-value key into the parent.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] Depth only increases when the root is split, maintaining balance.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] Similarly, a B-tree is kept balanced after deletion by merging or redistributing keys among siblings to maintain the d-key minimum for non-root nodes.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] A merger reduces the number of keys in the parent, potentially forcing it to merge or redistribute keys with its siblings, and so on.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] The only change in depth occurs when the root has two children, of d and (transitionally) $d-1$ keys, in which case the two siblings and parent are merged, reducing the depth by one.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] This depth will increase slowly as elements are added to the tree, but an increase in the overall depth is infrequent, and results in all leaf nodes being one more node farther away from the root.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] Because a range of child nodes is permitted, B-trees do not need re-balancing as frequently as other self-balancing search trees, but may waste some space since nodes are not entirely full.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] B-trees have substantial advantages over alternative implementations when the time to access the data of a node greatly exceeds the time spent processing that data, because the cost of accessing the node may then be amortized over multiple operations within the node.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] This usually occurs when the node data are stored in secondary storage, such as disk drives.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] By maximizing the number of keys within each internal node, the height of the tree decreases, and the number of expensive node accesses is reduced.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] In addition, rebalancing of the tree occurs less frequently.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] The maximum number of child nodes depends on the information that must be stored for each child node and the size of a full disk block or an analogous size in secondary storage.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] While 2–3 B-trees are easier to explain, practical B-trees using secondary storage need a large number of child nodes to improve performance.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] The term **B-tree** may refer to a specific design or a general class of designs.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] In the narrow sense, a B-tree stores keys in its internal nodes but need not store those keys in the records at the leaves.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] The general class includes variations such as the B+ tree, the B* tree and the B*+ tree.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] Sorting and searching algorithms can be characterized by the number of comparison operations that must be performed using order notation.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] A binary search of a sorted table with N records, for example, can be done in roughly ⌈ log2 *N* ⌉ comparisons.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] If the table had 1,000,000 records, then a specific record could be located with at most 20 comparisons: ⌈ log2 (1,000,000) ⌉ = 20.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] Large databases have historically been kept on disk drives.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] The time required to read a record on a disk drive far exceeds the time needed to compare keys once the record is available due to seek time and rotational delay.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] The seek time may be 0 to 20 or more milliseconds, and the rotational delay averages about half the rotation period.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] For a 7200 RPM drive, the rotation period is 8.33 milliseconds.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] For a drive such as the Seagate ST3500320NS, the track-to-track seek time is 0.8 milliseconds and the average reading seek time is 8.5 milliseconds.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] For simplicity, assume reading from disk takes about 10 milliseconds.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] The time required to locate one record out of a million in the example above would be 20 disk reads, each taking 10 milliseconds, which equals 0.2 seconds.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] The search time is reduced because individual records are grouped together in a disk **block**.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] A disk block might be 16 kilobytes in size.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] If each record is 160 bytes, then 100 records could be stored in each block.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] The disk read time above was actually for an entire block.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] Once the disk head is in position, one or more disk blocks can be read with little delay.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] With 100 records per block, the last 6 or so comparisons don't need to do any disk reads—the comparisons are all within the last disk block read.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] To speed up the search further, the time to do the first 13 to 14 comparisons (which each required disk access) must be reduced.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] A B-tree index can be used to improve performance.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] A B-tree index creates a multi-level tree structure that breaks a database down into fixed-size blocks or pages.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] Each level of this tree can be used to link those pages via an address location, allowing one page (known as a node, or internal page) to refer to another with leaf pages at the lowest level.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] One page is typically the starting point of the tree, or the "root".
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] This is where the search for a particular key would begin, traversing a path that terminates in a leaf.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] Most pages in this structure will be leaf pages which refer to specific table rows.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] Because each node (or internal page) can have more than two children, a B-tree index will usually have a shorter height (the distance from the root to the farthest leaf) than a Binary Search Tree.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] In the example above, initial disk reads narrowed the search range by a factor of two.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] That can be improved by creating an auxiliary index that contains the first record in each disk block (sometimes called a sparse index).
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] This auxiliary index would be 1% of the size of the original database, but it can be searched quickly.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] Finding an entry in the auxiliary index would tell us which block to search in the main database; after searching the auxiliary index, we would have to search only that one block of the main database—at a cost of one more disk read.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] In the above example, the index would hold 10,000 entries and would take at most 14 comparisons to return a result.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] Like the main database, the last six or so comparisons in the auxiliary index would be on the same disk block.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] The index could be searched in about eight disk reads, and the desired record could be accessed in 9 disk reads.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] Creating an auxiliary index can be repeated to make an auxiliary index to the auxiliary index.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] That would create an aux-aux index that would need only 100 entries and would fit in one disk block.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] Instead of reading 14 disk blocks to find the desired record, we only need to read 3 blocks.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] This blocking is the core idea behind the creation of the B-tree, where disk blocks form a hierarchy of levels to make up the index.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] Reading and searching the first (and only) block of the aux-aux index, which is the root of the tree, identifies the relevant block in aux-index in the level below.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] Reading and searching that aux-index block identifies the relevant block to read until the final level, known as the leaf level, identifies a record in the main database.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] Instead of 150 milliseconds, we need only 30 milliseconds to get the record.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] The auxiliary indices have turned the search problem from a binary search requiring roughly log2 *N* disk reads to one requiring only log*b* *N* disk reads where b is the blocking factor (the number of entries per block: *b* = 100 entries per block in our example; log100 1,000,000 = 3 reads).
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] In practice, if the main database is being frequently searched, the aux-aux index and much of the aux index may reside in a disk cache, so they would not incur a disk read.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] The B-tree remains the standard index implementation in almost all relational databases, and many nonrelational databases use it as well.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] If the database does not change, then compiling the index is simple to do, and the index need never be changed.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] If there are changes, managing the database and its index requires additional computation.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] Deleting records from a database is relatively easy.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] The index can stay the same, and the record can just be marked as deleted.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] If there are a large number of lazy deletions, then searching and storage become less efficient.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] Insertions can be very slow in a sorted sequential file because room for the inserted record must be made.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] Inserting a record before the first record requires shifting all of the records down one.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] Such an operation is just too expensive to be practical.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] Instead of densely packing all the records in a block, the block can have some free space to allow for subsequent insertions.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] Those spaces would be marked as if they were "deleted" records.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] Both insertions and deletions are fast as long as space is available on a block.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] If an insertion won't fit on the block, then some free space on some nearby block must be found and the auxiliary indices adjusted.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] The best case is that enough space is available nearby so that the amount of block reorganization can be minimized.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] Alternatively, some out-of-sequence disk blocks may be used.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] The B-tree uses all of the ideas described above.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] In addition, a B-tree minimizes waste by making sure the interior nodes are at least half full.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] A B-tree can handle an arbitrary number of insertions and deletions.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] Let *h* ≥ –1 be the height of the classic B-tree (see Tree (data structure) § Terminology for the tree height definition).
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] Let *n* ≥ 0 be the number of entries in the tree.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] Let *m* be the maximum number of children a node can have.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] It can be shown (by induction for example) that a B-tree of height *h* with all its nodes completely filled has *n* = *m**h*+1–1 entries.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] Let d be the minimum number of children an internal (non-root) node must have.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] Searching is similar to searching a binary search tree.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] Starting at the root, the tree is recursively traversed from top to bottom.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] At each level, the search reduces its field of view to the child pointer (subtree) whose range includes the search value.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] A subtree's range is defined by the values, or keys, contained in its parent node.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] These limiting values are also known as separation values.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] Binary search is typically (but not necessarily) used within nodes to find the separation values and child tree of interest.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] To insert a new element, search the tree to find the leaf node where the new element should be added.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] Values less than the median are put in the new left node, and values greater than the median are put in the new right node, with the median acting as a separation value.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] The separation value is inserted in the node's parent, which may cause it to be split, and so on.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] If the node has no parent (i.e., the node was the root), create a new root above this node (increasing the height of the tree).
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] If the splitting goes all the way up to the root, it creates a new root with a single separator value and two children, which is why the lower bound on the size of internal nodes does not apply to the root.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] The maximum number of elements per node is *U*−1.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] When a node is split, one element moves to the parent, but one element is added.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] So, it must be possible to divide the maximum number *U*−1 of elements into two legal nodes.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] If this number is odd, then *U*=2*L* and one of the new nodes contains (*U*−2)/2 = *L*−1 elements, and hence is a legal node, and the other contains one more element, and hence it is legal too.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] If *U*−1 is even, then *U*=2*L*−1, so there are 2*L*−2 elements in the node.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] Half of this number is *L*−1, which is the minimum number of elements allowed per node.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] An alternative algorithm supports a single pass down the tree from the root to the node where the insertion will take place, splitting any full nodes encountered on the way pre-emptively.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] This prevents the need to recall the parent nodes into memory, which may be expensive if the nodes are on secondary storage.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] However, to use this algorithm, we must be able to send one element to the parent and split the remaining *U*−2 elements into two legal nodes, without adding a new element.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] This requires *U* = 2*L* rather than *U* = 2*L*−1, which accounts for why some textbooks impose this requirement in defining B-trees.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] There are two popular strategies for deletion from a B-tree.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] Do a single pass down the tree, but before entering (visiting) a node, restructure the tree so that once the key to be deleted is encountered, it can be deleted without triggering the need for any further restructuring.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] The algorithm below uses the former strategy.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] Deleting an element may put its node under the minimum number of elements and children.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] The procedures for these cases are listed below.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] If the value is in a leaf node, simply delete it from the node.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] If underflow happens, rebalance the tree as described in the section "Rebalancing after deletion" below.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] Each element in an internal node acts as a separation value for two subtrees; we need to find a replacement for separation.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] Note that the largest element in the left subtree is still less than the separator.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] Likewise, the smallest element in the right subtree is still greater than the separator.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] Both of those elements are in leaf nodes, and either one can be the new separator for the two subtrees.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] The previous step deleted an element (the new separator) from a leaf node.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] If that leaf node is now deficient (has fewer than the required number of nodes), then rebalance the tree starting from the leaf node.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] Rebalancing starts from a leaf and proceeds toward the root until the tree is balanced.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] If deleting an element from a node has brought it under the minimum size, then some elements must be redistributed to bring all nodes up to the minimum.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] Usually, the redistribution involves moving an element from a sibling node that has more than the minimum number of nodes.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] That redistribution operation is called a **rotation**.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] If no sibling can spare an element, then the deficient node must be **merged** with a sibling.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] The merge causes the parent to lose a separator element, so the parent may become deficient and need rebalancing.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] The merging and rebalancing may continue all the way to the root.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] Since the minimum element count doesn't apply to the root, making the root be the only deficient node is not a problem.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] While freshly loaded databases tend to have good sequential behaviour, this behaviour becomes increasingly difficult to maintain as a database grows, resulting in more random I/O and performance challenges.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] A common special case is adding a large amount of *pre-sorted* data into an initially empty B-tree.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] While it is quite possible to simply perform a series of successive inserts, inserting sorted data results in a tree composed almost entirely of half-full nodes.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] Instead, a special "bulk loading" algorithm can be used to produce a more efficient tree with a higher branching factor.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] When the input is sorted, all insertions are at the rightmost edge of the tree, and in particular any time a node is split, we are guaranteed that no more insertions will take place in the left half.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] When bulk loading, we take advantage of this, and instead of splitting overfull nodes evenly, split them as *unevenly* as possible: leave the left node completely full and create a right node with zero keys and one child (in violation of the usual B-tree rules).
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] At the end of bulk loading, the tree is composed almost entirely of completely full nodes; only the rightmost node on each level may be less than full.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] Because those nodes may also be less than *half* full, to re-establish the normal B-tree rules, combine such nodes with their (guaranteed full) left siblings and divide the keys to produce two nodes at least half full.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] The only node which lacks a full left sibling is the root, which is permitted to be less than half full.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] In addition to its use in databases, the B-tree (or § Variants) is also used in filesystems to allow quick random access to an arbitrary block in a particular file.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] The basic problem is turning the file block i address into a disk block address.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] Some early operating systems, and some highly specialized ones, required the application to allocate the maximum size of a file when the file was created.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] The file can then be allocated as contiguous disk blocks.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] In that case, to convert the file block address i into a disk block address, the operating system simply adds the file block address i to the address of the first disk block constituting the file.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] The scheme is simple, but the file cannot exceed its created size.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] All modern, mainstream operating systems allow a file to grow.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] The resulting disk blocks may not be contiguous, so mapping logical blocks to physical blocks is more involved.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] MS-DOS, for example, used a simple File Allocation Table (FAT).
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] The FAT has an entry for each disk block, and that entry identifies whether its block is used by a file and if so, which block (if any) is the next disk block of the same file.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] So, the allocation of each file is represented as a linked list in the table.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] In order to find the disk address of file block i , the operating system (or disk utility) must sequentially follow the file's linked list in the FAT.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] Worse, to find a free disk block, it must sequentially scan the FAT.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] For MS-DOS, that was not a huge penalty because the disks and files were small and the FAT had few entries and relatively short file chains.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] In the FAT12 filesystem (used on floppy disks and early hard disks), there were no more than 4,080 entries, and the FAT would usually be resident in memory.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] As disks got bigger, the FAT architecture began to confront penalties.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] On a large disk using FAT, it may be necessary to perform disk reads to learn the disk location of a file block to be read or written.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] TOPS-20 used a 0 to 2 level tree that has similarities to a B-tree.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] If the file fit in a 512 (29) word block, then the file directory would point to that physical disk block.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] If the file fit in 218 words, then the directory would point to an aux index; the 512 words of that index would either be NULL (the block isn't allocated) or point to the physical address of the block.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] If the file fit in 227 words, then the directory would point to a block holding an aux-aux index; each entry would either be NULL or point to an aux index.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] Consequently, the physical disk block for a 227 word file could be located in two disk reads and read on the third.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] Apple's filesystem HFS+ and APFS, Microsoft's NTFS, AIX (jfs2) and some Linux filesystems, such as Bcachefs, Btrfs and ext4, use B-trees.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] B*-trees are used in the HFS and Reiser4 file systems.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] DragonFly BSD's HAMMER file system uses a modified B+-tree.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] A B-tree grows slower with growing data amount, than the linearity of a linked list.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] Compared to a skip list, both structures have the same performance, but the B-tree scales better for growing *n*.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] A T-tree, for main memory database systems, is similar but more compact.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] Lehman and Yao showed that all the read locks could be avoided (and thus concurrent access greatly improved) by linking the tree blocks at each level together with a "next" pointer.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] This results in a tree structure where both insertion and search operations descend from the root to the leaf.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] Write locks are only required as a tree block is modified.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] This maximizes access concurrency by multiple users, an important consideration for databases and/or other B-tree-based ISAM storage methods.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] The cost associated with this improvement is that empty pages cannot be removed from the btree during normal operations.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] United States Patent 5283894, granted in 1994, appears to show a way to use a 'Meta Access Method' to allow concurrent B+ tree access and modification without locks.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] The technique accesses the tree 'upwards' for both searches and updates by means of additional in-memory indexes that point at the blocks in each level in the block cache.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] No reorganization for deletes is needed and there are no 'next' pointers in each block as in Lehman and Yao.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] Since B-trees are similar in structure to red-black trees, parallel algorithms for red-black trees can be applied to B-trees as well.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] A Maple tree is a B-tree developed for use in the Linux kernel to reduce lock contention in virtual memory management.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] (a,b)-trees are generalizations of B-trees.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] B-trees require that each internal node have a minimum of $\lfloor K/2\rfloor +1$ children and a maximum of K children, for some preset value of K .
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] In contrast, an (a,b)-tree allows the minimum number of children for an internal node to be set arbitrarily low.
[src:index-tree-structures/b-tree] In an (a,b)-tree, each internal node has between a and b children, for some preset values of a and b.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] In computer science, a **hash table** is a data structure that implements an associative array, also called a **dictionary** or simply **map**; an associative array is an abstract data type that maps keys to values.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] A hash table uses a hash function to compute an *index*, also called a *hash code*, into an array of *buckets* or *slots*, from which the desired value can be found.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] During lookup, the key is hashed and the resulting hash indicates where the corresponding value is stored.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] A map implemented by a hash table is called a **hash map**.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] Most hash table designs employ an imperfect hash function.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] Hash collisions, where the hash function generates the same index for more than one key, therefore typically must be accommodated in some way.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] Common strategies to handle hash collisions include chaining, which stores multiple elements in the same slot using linked lists, and open addressing, which searches for the next available slot according to a probing sequence.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] In a well-dimensioned hash table, the average time complexity for each lookup is independent of the number of elements stored in the table.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] Many hash table designs also allow arbitrary insertions and deletions of key–value pairs, at amortized constant average cost per operation.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] Hashing is an example of a space–time tradeoff.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] If memory is infinite, the entire key can be used directly as an index to locate its value with a single memory access.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] On the other hand, if infinite time is available, values can be stored without regard for their keys, and a binary search or linear search can be used to retrieve the element.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] In many situations, hash tables turn out to be on average more efficient than search trees or any other table lookup structure.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] For this reason, they are widely used in many kinds of computer software, particularly for associative arrays, database indexing, caches, and sets.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] Many programming languages provide built-in hash table structures, such as Python’s dictionaries, Java’s HashMap, C++’s unordered_map, Go maps, which abstract the complexity of hashing from the programmer.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] The idea of hashing arose independently in different places.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] In January 1953, Hans Peter Luhn wrote an internal IBM memorandum that used hashing with chaining.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] The first example of open addressing was proposed by A.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] Around the same time, Gene Amdahl, Elaine M.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] McGraw, Nathaniel Rochester, and Arthur Samuel of IBM Research implemented hashing for the IBM 701 assembler.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] Open addressing with linear probing is credited to Amdahl, although Andrey Ershov independently had the same idea.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] The term "open addressing" was coined by W.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] Wesley Peterson in his article which discusses the problem of search in large files.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] The first published work on hashing with chaining is credited to Arnold Dumey, who discussed the idea of using remainder modulo a prime as a hash function.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] The word "hashing" was first published in an article by Robert Morris.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] A theoretical analysis of linear probing was submitted originally by Konheim and Weiss.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] An associative array stores a set of (key, value) pairs and allows insertion, deletion, and lookup (search), with the constraint of unique keys.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] In the hash table implementation of associative arrays, an array A of length m is partially filled with n elements, where $m\geq n$ .
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] A key **x** is hashed using a hash function h to compute an index location $A[h(x)]$ in the hash table, where $h(x)<m$ .
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] The efficiency of a hash table depends on the load factor, defined as the ratio of the number of stored elements to the number of available slots, with lower load factors generally yielding faster operations.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] At this index, both the key and its associated value are stored.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] Storing the key alongside the value ensures that lookups can verify the key at the index to retrieve the correct value, even in the presence of collisions.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] Under reasonable assumptions, hash tables have better time complexity bounds on search, delete, and insert operations in comparison to self-balancing binary search trees.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] Hash tables are also commonly used to implement sets, by omitting the stored value for each key and merely tracking whether the key is present.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] The performance of the hash table deteriorates in relation to the load factor $\alpha$ .
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] In the limit of large m and n , each bucket statistically has a Poisson distribution with expectation $\lambda =\alpha$ for an ideally random hash function.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] The software typically ensures that the load factor $\alpha$ remains below a certain constant, $\alpha _{\max }$ .
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] Therefore, a common approach is to resize or "rehash" the hash table whenever the load factor $\alpha$ reaches $\alpha _{\max }$ .
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] Similarly the table may also be resized if the load factor drops below $\alpha _{\max }/4$ .
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] With separate chaining hash tables, each slot of the bucket array stores a pointer to a list or array of data.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] Separate chaining hash tables suffer gradually declining performance as the load factor grows, and no fixed point beyond which resizing is absolutely needed.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] With separate chaining, the value of $\alpha _{\max }$ that gives best performance is typically between 1 and 3.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] With open addressing, each slot of the bucket array holds exactly one item.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] Therefore an open-addressed hash table cannot have a load factor greater than 1.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] The performance of open addressing becomes very bad when the load factor approaches 1.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] Therefore a hash table that uses open addressing *must* be resized or *rehashed* if the load factor $\alpha$ approaches 1.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] With open addressing, acceptable figures of max load factor $\alpha _{\max }$ should range around 0.6 to 0.75.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] A hash function $h:U\rightarrow \{0,...,m-1\}$ maps the universe U of keys to indices or slots within the table, that is, $h(x)\in \{0,...,m-1\}$ for $x\in U$ .
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] The conventional implementations of hash functions are based on the *integer universe assumption* that all elements of the table stem from the universe $U=\{0,...,u-1\}$ , where the bit length of u is confined within the word size of a computer architecture.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] A hash function h is said to be perfect for a given set S if it is injective on S , that is, if each element $x\in S$ maps to a different value in ${0,...,m-1}$ .
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] A perfect hash function can be created if all the keys are known ahead of time.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] The schemes of hashing used in *integer universe assumption* include hashing by division, hashing by multiplication, universal hashing, dynamic perfect hashing, and static perfect hashing.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] However, hashing by division is the commonly used scheme.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] The scheme in hashing by division is as follows: $h(x)\ =\ x\,{\bmod {\,}}m,$ where $h(x)$ is the hash value of $x\in S$ and m is the size of the table.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] The scheme in hashing by multiplication is as follows: $h(x)=\lfloor m{\bigl (}(xA){\bmod {1}}{\bigr )}\rfloor$ Where A is a non-integer real-valued constant and m is the size of the table.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] An advantage of the hashing by multiplication is that the m is not critical.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] Although any value A produces a hash function, Donald Knuth suggests using the golden ratio.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] Commonly a string is used as a key to the hash function.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] The third edition of *The C++ Programming Language* describes a simple hash function in which an unsigned integer that is initially zero is repeatedly left shifted one bit and then xor'ed with the integer value of the next character.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] This hash value is then taken modulo the table size.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] If the left shift is not circular, then the string length should be at least eight bits less than the size of the unsigned integer in bits.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] Another common way to hash a string to an integer is with a polynomial rolling hash function.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] Uniform distribution of the hash values is a fundamental requirement of a hash function.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] A non-uniform distribution increases the number of collisions and the cost of resolving them.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] Uniformity is sometimes difficult to ensure by design, but may be evaluated empirically using statistical tests, e.g., a Pearson's chi-squared test for discrete uniform distributions.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] The distribution needs to be uniform only for table sizes that occur in the application.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] In particular, if one uses dynamic resizing with exact doubling and halving of the table size, then the hash function needs to be uniform only when the size is a power of two.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] Here the index can be computed as some range of bits of the hash function.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] On the other hand, some hashing algorithms prefer to have the size be a prime number.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] For open addressing schemes, the hash function should also avoid *runs*, the mapping of two or more keys to consecutive slots.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] Such runs may cause the lookup cost to skyrocket, even if the load factor is low and collisions are infrequent.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] The popular multiplicative hash is claimed to have particularly poor run behavior.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] K-independent hashing offers a way to prove a certain hash function does not have bad keysets for a given type of hashtable.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] A number of K-independence results are known for collision resolution schemes such as linear probing and cuckoo hashing.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] Since K-independence can prove a hash function works, one can then focus on finding the fastest possible such hash function.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] A search algorithm that uses hashing consists of two parts.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] The first part is computing a hash function which transforms the search key into an array index.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] The ideal case is such that no two search keys hash to the same array index.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] However, this is not always the case and impossible to guarantee for unseen given data.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] Hence the second part of the algorithm is collision resolution.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] The two common methods for collision resolution are separate chaining and open addressing.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] In separate chaining, the process involves building a linked list with key–value pair for each search array index.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] The collided items are chained together through a single linked list, which can be traversed to access the item with a unique search key.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] Collision resolution through chaining with linked list is a common method of implementation of hash tables.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] If the element is comparable either numerically or lexically, and inserted into the list by maintaining the total order, it results in faster termination of the unsuccessful searches.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] If the keys are ordered, it could be efficient to use "self-organizing" concepts such as using a self-balancing binary search tree, through which the theoretical worst case could be brought down to $O(\log {n})$ , although it introduces additional complexities.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] In dynamic perfect hashing, two-level hash tables are used to reduce the look-up complexity to be a guaranteed $O(1)$ in the worst case.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] In this technique, the buckets of k entries are organized as perfect hash tables with $k^{2}$ slots providing constant worst-case lookup time, and low amortized time for insertion.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] A study shows array-based separate chaining to be 97% more performant when compared to the standard linked list method under heavy load.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] Techniques such as using fusion tree for each buckets also result in constant time for all operations with high probability.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] The linked list of separate chaining implementation may not be cache-conscious due to spatial locality—locality of reference—when the nodes of the linked list are scattered across memory, thus the list traversal during insert and search may entail CPU cache inefficiencies.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] Open addressing is another collision resolution technique in which every entry record is stored in the bucket array itself, and the hash resolution is performed through **probing**.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] When a new entry has to be inserted, the buckets are examined, starting with the hashed-to slot and proceeding in some *probe sequence*, until an unoccupied slot is found.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] When searching for an entry, the buckets are scanned in the same sequence, until either the target record is found, or an unused array slot is found, which indicates an unsuccessful search.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] The performance of open addressing may be slower compared to separate chaining since the probe sequence increases when the load factor $\alpha$ approaches 1.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] The probing results in an infinite loop if the load factor reaches 1, in the case of a completely filled table.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] The average cost of linear probing depends on the hash function's ability to distribute the elements uniformly throughout the table to avoid runs, since formation of runs would result in increased search time.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] Since the slots are located in successive locations, linear probing could lead to better utilization of CPU cache due to locality of references resulting in reduced memory latency.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] Coalesced hashing is a hybrid of both separate chaining and open addressing in which the buckets or nodes link within the table.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] The algorithm is ideally suited for fixed memory allocation.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] The collision in coalesced hashing is resolved by identifying the largest-indexed empty slot on the hash table, then the colliding value is inserted into that slot.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] The bucket is also linked to the inserted node's slot which contains its colliding hash address.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] Cuckoo hashing is a form of open addressing collision resolution technique which guarantees $O(1)$ worst-case lookup complexity and constant amortized time for insertions.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] The collision is resolved through maintaining two hash tables, each having its own hashing function, and collided slot gets replaced with the given item, and the preoccupied element of the slot gets displaced into the other hash table.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] The process continues until every key has its own spot in the empty buckets of the tables; if the procedure enters into infinite loop—which is identified through maintaining a threshold loop counter—both hash tables get rehashed with newer hash functions and the procedure continues.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] Hopscotch hashing is an open addressing based algorithm which combines the elements of cuckoo hashing, linear probing and chaining through the notion of a *neighbourhood* of buckets—the subsequent buckets around any given occupied bucket, also called a "virtual" bucket.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] The algorithm is designed to deliver better performance when the load factor of the hash table grows beyond 90%; it also provides high throughput in concurrent settings, thus well suited for implementing resizable concurrent hash table.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] Each bucket within the hash table includes an additional "hop-information"—an *H*-bit bit array for indicating the relative distance of the item which was originally hashed into the current virtual bucket within *H* − 1 entries.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] *H* − 1, subsequent swap and hop-info bit array manipulation of each bucket is performed in accordance with its neighbourhood invariant properties.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] Robin Hood hashing is an open addressing based collision resolution algorithm; the collisions are resolved through favouring the displacement of the element that is farthest—or longest *probe sequence length* (PSL)—from its "home location" i.e. the bucket to which the item was hashed into.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] It is named after Robin Hood, a mythical heroic outlaw who stole from the rich to give to the poor.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] Although Robin Hood hashing does not change the theoretical search cost, it significantly affects the variance of the distribution of the items on the buckets, i.e. dealing with long run formation in the hash table.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] Each node within the hash table that uses Robin Hood hashing should be augmented to store an extra PSL value.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] If a hash table becomes "too empty" after deleting some elements, resizing may be performed to avoid excessive memory usage.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] Generally, a new hash table with a size double that of the original hash table gets allocated privately and every item in the original hash table gets moved to the newly allocated one by computing the hash values of the items followed by the insertion operation.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] Rehashing is simple, but computationally expensive.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] Some hash table implementations, notably in real-time systems, cannot pay the price of enlarging the hash table all at once, because it may interrupt time-critical operations.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] If one cannot avoid dynamic resizing, a solution is to perform the resizing gradually to avoid storage blip—typically at 50% of new table's size—during rehashing and to avoid memory fragmentation that triggers heap compaction due to deallocation of large memory blocks caused by the old hash table.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] In such case, the rehashing operation is done incrementally through extending prior memory block allocated for the old hash table such that the buckets of the hash table remain unaltered.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] A common approach for amortized rehashing involves maintaining two hash functions $h_{\text{old}}$ and $h_{\text{new}}$ .
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] Linear hashing is an implementation of the hash table which enables dynamic growths or shrinks of the table one bucket at a time.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] The performance of a hash table is dependent on the hash function's ability in generating quasi-random numbers ( $\sigma$ ) for entries in the hash table where K , n and $h(x)$ denotes the key, number of buckets and the hash function such that $\sigma \ =\ h(K)\ \%\ n$ .
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] If the hash function generates the same $\sigma$ for distinct keys ( $K_{1}\neq K_{2},\ h(K_{1})\ =\ h(K_{2})$ ), this results in *collision*, which is dealt with in a variety of ways.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] The constant time complexity ( $O(1)$ ) of the operation in a hash table is presupposed on the condition that the hash function doesn't generate colliding indices; thus, the performance of the hash table is directly proportional to the chosen hash function's ability to disperse the indices.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] However, construction of such a hash function is practically infeasible, that being so, implementations depend on case-specific collision resolution techniques in achieving higher performance.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] The best performance is obtained in the case that the hash function distributes the elements of the universe uniformaly, and the elements stored at the table are drawn at random from the universe.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] In this case, in hashing with chaining, the expected time for a successful search is ${\textstyle 1+{\frac {\alpha }{2}}+\Theta \left({\frac {1}{m}}\right)}$ , and the expected time for an unsuccessful search is ${\textstyle e^{-\alpha }+\alpha +\Theta \left({\frac {1}{m}}\right)}$ .
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] Hash tables are commonly used to implement many types of in-memory tables.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] They are used to implement associative arrays.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] Hash tables may also be used as disk-based data structures and database indices (such as in dbm) although B-trees are more popular in these applications.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] Hash tables can be used to implement caches, auxiliary data tables that are used to speed up the access to data that is primarily stored in slower media.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] In this application, hash collisions can be handled by discarding one of the two colliding entries—usually erasing the old item that is currently stored in the table and overwriting it with the new item, so every item in the table has a unique hash value.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] Hash tables can be used in the implementation of set data structure, which can store unique values without any particular order; set is typically used in testing the membership of a value in the collection, rather than element retrieval.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] A transposition table to a complex Hash Table which stores information about each section that has been searched.
[src:index-tree-structures/hash-table] Many programming languages provide hash table functionality, either as built-in associative arrays or as standard library modules.
[src:index-tree-structures/k-d-tree] In computer science, a ***k*-d tree** (short for *k-dimensional tree*) is a space-partitioning data structure for organizing points in a *k*-dimensional space.
[src:index-tree-structures/k-d-tree] K-dimensional is that which concerns exactly k orthogonal axes or a space of any number of dimensions.
[src:index-tree-structures/k-d-tree] The *k*-d tree is a binary tree in which *every* node is a *k*-dimensional point.
[src:index-tree-structures/k-d-tree] Every non-leaf node can be thought of as implicitly generating a splitting hyperplane that divides the space into two parts, known as half-spaces.
[src:index-tree-structures/k-d-tree] Points to the left of this hyperplane are represented by the left subtree of that node and points to the right of the hyperplane are represented by the right subtree.
[src:index-tree-structures/k-d-tree] The hyperplane direction is chosen in the following way: every node in the tree is associated with one of the *k* dimensions, with the hyperplane perpendicular to that dimension's axis.
[src:index-tree-structures/k-d-tree] So, for example, if for a particular split the "x" axis is chosen, all points in the subtree with a smaller "x" value than the node will appear in the left subtree and all points with a larger "x" value will be in the right subtree.
[src:index-tree-structures/k-d-tree] In such a case, the hyperplane would be set by the x value of the point, and its normal would be the unit x-axis.
[src:index-tree-structures/k-d-tree] Since there are many possible ways to choose axis-aligned splitting planes, there are many different ways to construct *k*-d trees.
[src:index-tree-structures/k-d-tree] This method leads to a balanced *k*-d tree, in which each leaf node is approximately the same distance from the root.
[src:index-tree-structures/k-d-tree] However, balanced trees are not necessarily optimal for all applications.
[src:index-tree-structures/k-d-tree] Note that it is not *required* to select the median point.
[src:index-tree-structures/k-d-tree] In the case where median points are not selected, there is no guarantee that the tree will be balanced.
[src:index-tree-structures/k-d-tree] To avoid coding a complex $O(n)$ median-finding algorithm or using an $O(n\log(n))$ sort such as heapsort or mergesort to sort all *n* points, a popular practice is to sort a *fixed* number of *randomly* *selected* points, and use the median of those points to serve as the splitting plane.
[src:index-tree-structures/k-d-tree] In practice, this technique often results in nicely balanced trees.
[src:index-tree-structures/k-d-tree] Given a list of *n* points, the following algorithm uses a median-finding sort to construct a balanced *k*-d tree containing those points.
[src:index-tree-structures/k-d-tree] It is common that points "after" the median include only the ones that are strictly greater than the median in the current dimension.
[src:index-tree-structures/k-d-tree] For points that lie on the median in the current dimension, it is possible to define a function that compares them in all dimensions.
[src:index-tree-structures/k-d-tree] In some cases, it is acceptable to let points equal to the median lie on one side of the median, for example, by splitting the points into a "lesser than" subset and a "greater than or equal to" subset.
[src:index-tree-structures/k-d-tree] This algorithm creates the invariant that for any node, all the nodes in the left subtree are on one side of a splitting plane, and all the nodes in the right subtree are on the other side.
[src:index-tree-structures/k-d-tree] Points that lie on the splitting plane may appear on either side.
[src:index-tree-structures/k-d-tree] The splitting plane of a node goes through the point associated with that node (referred to in the code as *node.location*).
[src:index-tree-structures/k-d-tree] Alternative algorithms for building a balanced *k*-d tree presort the data prior to building the tree.
[src:index-tree-structures/k-d-tree] Then, they maintain the order of the presort during tree construction and hence eliminate the costly step of finding the median at each level of subdivision.
[src:index-tree-structures/k-d-tree] Two such algorithms build a balanced *k*-d tree to sort triangles in order to improve the execution time of ray tracing for three-dimensional computer graphics.
[src:index-tree-structures/k-d-tree] These algorithms presort *n* triangles prior to building the *k*-d tree, then build the tree in $O(n\log n)$ time in the best case.
[src:index-tree-structures/k-d-tree] An algorithm that builds a balanced *k*-d tree to sort points has a worst-case complexity of $O(kn\log(n))$ .
[src:index-tree-structures/k-d-tree] This algorithm presorts *n* points in each of *k* dimensions using an $O(n\log(n))$ sort such as Heapsort or Mergesort prior to building the tree.
[src:index-tree-structures/k-d-tree] It then maintains the order of these *k* presorts during tree construction and thereby avoids finding the median at each level of subdivision.
[src:index-tree-structures/k-d-tree] One adds a new point to a *k*-d tree in the same way as one adds an element to any other search tree.
[src:index-tree-structures/k-d-tree] First, traverse the tree, starting from the root and moving to either the left or the right child depending on whether the point to be inserted is on the "left" or "right" side of the splitting plane.
[src:index-tree-structures/k-d-tree] Once you get to the node under which the child should be located, add the new point as either the left or right child of the leaf node, again depending on which side of the node's splitting plane contains the new node.
[src:index-tree-structures/k-d-tree] Adding points in this manner can cause the tree to become unbalanced, leading to decreased tree performance.
[src:index-tree-structures/k-d-tree] The rate of tree performance degradation is dependent upon the spatial distribution of tree points being added, and the number of points added in relation to the tree size.
[src:index-tree-structures/k-d-tree] If a tree becomes too unbalanced, it may need to be re-balanced to restore the performance of queries that rely on the tree balancing, such as nearest neighbour searching.
[src:index-tree-structures/k-d-tree] To remove a point from an existing *k*-d tree without breaking the invariant, the easiest way is to form the set of all nodes and leaves from the children of the target node and recreate that part of the tree.
[src:index-tree-structures/k-d-tree] Another approach is to find a replacement for the point removed.
[src:index-tree-structures/k-d-tree] First, find the node R that contains the point to be removed.
[src:index-tree-structures/k-d-tree] For the base case, where R is a leaf node, no replacement is required.
[src:index-tree-structures/k-d-tree] For the general case, find a replacement point, say p , from the subtree rooted at R .
[src:index-tree-structures/k-d-tree] For finding a replacement point, if R discriminates on x (say) and R has a right child, find the point with the minimum x value from the subtree rooted at the right child.
[src:index-tree-structures/k-d-tree] Otherwise, find the point with the maximum x value from the subtree rooted at the left child.
[src:index-tree-structures/k-d-tree] Balancing a *k*-d tree requires care because *k*-d trees are sorted in multiple dimensions, so the tree-rotation technique cannot be used to balance them as this may break the invariant.
[src:index-tree-structures/k-d-tree] Several variants of balanced *k*-d trees exist.
[src:index-tree-structures/k-d-tree] They include divided *k*-d tree, pseudo *k*-d tree, K-D-B-tree, hB-tree and Bkd-tree.
[src:index-tree-structures/k-d-tree] Many of these variants are adaptive k-d trees.
[src:index-tree-structures/k-d-tree] The nearest neighbour search (NN) algorithm aims to find the point in the tree that is nearest to a given input point.
[src:index-tree-structures/k-d-tree] This search can be done efficiently by using the tree properties to quickly eliminate large portions of the search space.
[src:index-tree-structures/k-d-tree] Once the algorithm reaches a leaf node, it checks the node point and if the distance is better than the "current best", that node point is saved as the "current best".
[src:index-tree-structures/k-d-tree] The algorithm checks whether there could be any points on the other side of the splitting plane that are closer to the search point than the current best.
[src:index-tree-structures/k-d-tree] In concept, this is done by intersecting the splitting hyperplane with a hypersphere around the search point that has a radius equal to the current nearest distance.
[src:index-tree-structures/k-d-tree] Since the hyperplanes are all axis-aligned this is implemented as a simple comparison to see whether the distance between the splitting coordinate of the search point and current node is less than the distance (overall coordinates) from the search point to the current best.
[src:index-tree-structures/k-d-tree] If the hypersphere doesn't intersect the splitting plane, then the algorithm continues walking up the tree, and the entire branch on the other side of that node is eliminated.
[src:index-tree-structures/k-d-tree] When the algorithm finishes this process for the root node, then the search is complete.
[src:index-tree-structures/k-d-tree] Generally the algorithm uses squared distances for comparison to avoid computing square roots.
[src:index-tree-structures/k-d-tree] Additionally, it can save computation by holding the squared current best distance in a variable for comparison.
[src:index-tree-structures/k-d-tree] The algorithm can be extended in several ways by simple modifications.
[src:index-tree-structures/k-d-tree] It can provide the *k* nearest neighbours to a point by maintaining *k* current bests instead of just one.
[src:index-tree-structures/k-d-tree] A branch is only eliminated when *k* points have been found and the branch cannot have points closer than any of the *k* current bests.
[src:index-tree-structures/k-d-tree] It can also be converted to an approximation algorithm to run faster.
[src:index-tree-structures/k-d-tree] For example, approximate nearest neighbour searching can be achieved by simply setting an upper bound on the number of points to examine in the tree or by interrupting the search process based upon a real time clock (which may be more appropriate in hardware implementations).
[src:index-tree-structures/k-d-tree] The nearest neighbour for points that are already in the tree can be achieved by not updating the refinement for nodes that give zero distance.
[src:index-tree-structures/k-d-tree] As a result, this has the downside of discarding points that are not unique but are co-located with the original search point.
[src:index-tree-structures/k-d-tree] Approximate nearest neighbour is useful in real-time applications such as robotics due to the significant speed increase gained by not searching for the best point exhaustively.
[src:index-tree-structures/k-d-tree] One of its implementations is best-bin-first search.
[src:index-tree-structures/k-d-tree] A range search searches for ranges of parameters.
[src:index-tree-structures/k-d-tree] For example, if a tree is storing values corresponding to income and age, then a range search might be something like looking for all members of the tree which have an age between 20 and 50 years and an income between 50,000 and 80,000.
[src:index-tree-structures/k-d-tree] Since k-d trees divide the range of a domain in half at each level of the tree, they are useful for performing range searches.
[src:index-tree-structures/k-d-tree] Analyses of binary search trees has found that the worst case time for range search in a *k*-dimensional *k*-d tree containing *n* nodes is given by the following equation.
[src:index-tree-structures/k-d-tree] In low-dimensional spaces, the nearest point is an $O(\log(n))$ operation on average, in the case of randomly distributed points, although analysis in general is tricky.
[src:index-tree-structures/k-d-tree] In high-dimensional spaces, the curse of dimensionality causes the algorithm to need to visit many more branches than in lower-dimensional spaces.
[src:index-tree-structures/k-d-tree] In particular, when the number of points is only slightly higher than the number of dimensions, the algorithm is only slightly better than a linear search of all of the points.
[src:index-tree-structures/k-d-tree] As a general rule, if the dimensionality is *k*, the number of points in the data, *n*, should be $n\gg 2^{k}$ .
[src:index-tree-structures/k-d-tree] Otherwise, when *k*-d trees are used with high-dimensional data, most of the points in the tree will be evaluated and the efficiency is no better than exhaustive search, and, if a good-enough fast answer is required, approximate nearest-neighbour methods should be used instead.
[src:index-tree-structures/k-d-tree] (In the worst case, consider a cloud of points distributed on the surface of a sphere centered at the origin.
[src:index-tree-structures/k-d-tree] This may result in a nearest neighbor search failing to return a nearest neighbor, which means no points are within this maximum distance from the query point.
[src:index-tree-structures/k-d-tree] Instead of points, a *k*-d tree can also contain rectangles or hyperrectangles.
[src:index-tree-structures/k-d-tree] Thus range search becomes the problem of returning all rectangles intersecting the search rectangle.
[src:index-tree-structures/k-d-tree] The tree is constructed the usual way with all the rectangles at the leaves.
[src:index-tree-structures/k-d-tree] In an orthogonal range search, the *opposite* coordinate is used when comparing against the median.
[src:index-tree-structures/k-d-tree] For example, if the current level is split along xhigh, we check the xlow coordinate of the search rectangle.
[src:index-tree-structures/k-d-tree] If the median is less than the xlow coordinate of the search rectangle, then no rectangle in the left branch can ever intersect with the search rectangle and so can be pruned.
[src:index-tree-structures/k-d-tree] Otherwise both branches should be traversed.
[src:index-tree-structures/k-d-tree] See also interval tree, which is a 1-dimensional special case.
[src:index-tree-structures/k-d-tree] It is also possible to define a *k*-d tree with points stored solely in leaves.
[src:index-tree-structures/k-d-tree] This form of *k*-d tree allows a variety of split mechanics other than the standard median split.
[src:index-tree-structures/k-d-tree] The midpoint splitting rule selects on the middle of the longest axis of the space being searched, regardless of the distribution of points.
[src:index-tree-structures/k-d-tree] This guarantees that the aspect ratio will be at most 2:1, but the depth is dependent on the distribution of points.
[src:index-tree-structures/k-d-tree] A variation, called sliding-midpoint, only splits on the middle if there are points on both sides of the split.
[src:index-tree-structures/k-d-tree] Otherwise, it splits on point nearest to the middle.
[src:index-tree-structures/k-d-tree] Maneewongvatana and Mount show that this offers "good enough" performance on common data sets.
[src:index-tree-structures/k-d-tree] Using sliding-midpoint, an approximate nearest neighbour query can be answered in $O\left({\tfrac {1}{{\epsilon \ }^{d}}}\log n\right)$ .
[src:index-tree-structures/k-d-tree] Approximate range counting can be answered in $O\left(\log n+{\left({\tfrac {1}{\epsilon \ }}\right)}^{d}\right)$ with this method.
[src:index-tree-structures/r-tree] The key idea of the data structure is to group nearby objects and represent them with their minimum bounding rectangle in the next higher level of the tree; the "R" in R-tree is for rectangle.
[src:index-tree-structures/r-tree] Since all objects lie within this bounding rectangle, a query that does not intersect the bounding rectangle also cannot intersect any of the contained objects.
[src:index-tree-structures/r-tree] At the leaf level, each rectangle describes a single object; at higher levels the aggregation includes an increasing number of objects.
[src:index-tree-structures/r-tree] This can also be seen as an increasingly coarse approximation of the data set.
[src:index-tree-structures/r-tree] Similar to the B-tree, the R-tree is also a balanced search tree (so all leaf nodes are at the same depth), organizes the data in pages, and is designed for storage on disk (as used in databases).
[src:index-tree-structures/r-tree] Each page can contain a maximum number of entries, often denoted as M .
[src:index-tree-structures/r-tree] It also guarantees a minimum fill (except for the root node), however best performance has been experienced with a minimum fill of 30%–40% of the maximum number of entries (B-trees guarantee 50% page fill, and B*-trees even 66%).
[src:index-tree-structures/r-tree] The reason for this is the more complex balancing required for spatial data as opposed to linear data stored in B-trees.
[src:index-tree-structures/r-tree] As with most trees, the searching algorithms (e.g., intersection, containment, nearest neighbor search) are rather simple.
[src:index-tree-structures/r-tree] The key idea is to use the bounding boxes to decide whether or not to search inside a subtree.
[src:index-tree-structures/r-tree] In this way, most of the nodes in the tree are never read during a search.
[src:index-tree-structures/r-tree] Like B-trees, R-trees are suitable for large data sets and databases, where nodes can be paged to memory when needed, and the whole tree cannot be kept in main memory.
[src:index-tree-structures/r-tree] Even if data can be fit in memory (or cached), the R-trees in most practical applications will usually provide performance advantages over naive check of all objects when the number of objects is more than few hundred or so.
[src:index-tree-structures/r-tree] However, for in-memory applications, there are similar alternatives that can provide slightly better performance or be simpler to implement in practice.
[src:index-tree-structures/r-tree] To maintain in-memory computing for R-tree in a computer cluster where computing nodes are connected by a network, researchers have used RDMA (Remote Direct Memory Access) to implement data-intensive applications under R-tree in a distributed environment.
[src:index-tree-structures/r-tree] This approach is scalable for increasingly large applications and achieves high throughput and low latency performance for R-tree.
[src:index-tree-structures/r-tree] The key difficulty of R-tree is to build an efficient tree that on one hand is balanced (so the leaf nodes are at the same height) on the other hand the rectangles do not cover too much empty space and do not overlap too much (so that during search, fewer subtrees need to be processed).
[src:index-tree-structures/r-tree] For example, the original idea for inserting elements to obtain an efficient tree is to always insert into the subtree that requires least enlargement of its bounding box.
[src:index-tree-structures/r-tree] Once that page is full, the data is split into two sets that should cover the minimal area each.
[src:index-tree-structures/r-tree] Most of the research and improvements for R-trees aims at improving the way the tree is built and can be grouped into two objectives: building an efficient tree from scratch (known as bulk-loading) and performing changes on an existing tree (insertion and deletion).
[src:index-tree-structures/r-tree] R-trees do not guarantee good worst-case performance, but generally perform well with real-world data.
[src:index-tree-structures/r-tree] The (bulk-loaded) Priority R-tree variant of the R-tree is worst-case optimal, but due to its increased complexity it has remained confined to theoretical study and has not received much attention in practical applications.
[src:index-tree-structures/r-tree] When data is organized in an R-tree, the neighbors within a given distance r and the k nearest neighbors (for any Lp-Norm) of all points can efficiently be computed using a spatial join.
[src:index-tree-structures/r-tree] This is beneficial for many algorithms based on such queries, for example the Local Outlier Factor.
[src:index-tree-structures/r-tree] DeLi-Clu, Density-Link-Clustering is a cluster analysis algorithm that uses the R-tree structure for a similar kind of spatial join to efficiently compute an OPTICS clustering.
[src:index-tree-structures/r-tree] Data in R-trees is organized in pages that can have a variable number of entries (up to some pre-defined maximum, and usually above a minimum fill).
[src:index-tree-structures/r-tree] Each entry within a non-leaf node stores two pieces of data: a way of identifying a child node, and the bounding box of all entries within this child node.
[src:index-tree-structures/r-tree] Leaf nodes store the data required for each child, often a point or bounding box representing the child and an external identifier for the child.
[src:index-tree-structures/r-tree] For point data, the leaf entries can be just the points themselves.
[src:index-tree-structures/r-tree] For polygon data (that often requires the storage of large polygons) the common setup is to store only the MBR (minimum bounding rectangle) of the polygon along with a unique identifier in the tree.
[src:index-tree-structures/r-tree] The search process in an R-tree embodies a two-phase approach that aligns with the Filter and Refine Principle (FRP).
[src:index-tree-structures/r-tree] In this structure, the internal nodes serve as an initial filter by quickly excluding regions of space that do not intersect the query, while the leaf nodes provide a refined, precise evaluation by storing the actual spatial objects.
[src:index-tree-structures/r-tree] Specifically, in range searching, the input is a search rectangle (Query box).
[src:index-tree-structures/r-tree] Searching is quite similar to searching in a B+ tree.
[src:index-tree-structures/r-tree] The search starts from the root node of the tree.
[src:index-tree-structures/r-tree] Every internal node contains a set of rectangles and pointers to the corresponding child node and every leaf node contains the rectangles of spatial objects (the pointer to some spatial object can be there).
[src:index-tree-structures/r-tree] For every rectangle in a node, it has to be decided if it overlaps the search rectangle or not.
[src:index-tree-structures/r-tree] If yes, the corresponding child node has to be searched also.
[src:index-tree-structures/r-tree] Searching is done like this in a recursive manner until all overlapping nodes have been traversed.
[src:index-tree-structures/r-tree] When a leaf node is reached, the contained bounding boxes (rectangles) are tested against the search rectangle and their objects (if there are any) are put into the result set if they lie within the search rectangle.
[src:index-tree-structures/r-tree] For priority search such as nearest neighbor search, the query consists of a point or rectangle.
[src:index-tree-structures/r-tree] The root node is inserted into the priority queue.
[src:index-tree-structures/r-tree] Until the queue is empty or the desired number of results have been returned the search continues by processing the nearest entry in the queue.
[src:index-tree-structures/r-tree] Tree nodes are expanded and their children reinserted.
[src:index-tree-structures/r-tree] Leaf entries are returned when encountered in the queue.
[src:index-tree-structures/r-tree] This approach can be used with various distance metrics, including great-circle distance for geographic data.
[src:index-tree-structures/r-tree] To insert an object, the tree is traversed recursively from the root node.
[src:index-tree-structures/r-tree] At each step, all rectangles in the current directory node are examined, and a candidate is chosen using a heuristic such as choosing the rectangle which requires least enlargement.
[src:index-tree-structures/r-tree] The search then descends into this page, until reaching a leaf node.
[src:index-tree-structures/r-tree] If the leaf node is full, it must be split before the insertion is made.
[src:index-tree-structures/r-tree] Again, since an exhaustive search is too expensive, a heuristic is employed to split the node into two.
[src:index-tree-structures/r-tree] Adding the newly created node to the previous level, this level can again overflow, and these overflows can propagate up to the root node; when this node also overflows, a new root node is created and the tree has increased in height.
[src:index-tree-structures/r-tree] The algorithm needs to decide in which subtree to insert.
[src:index-tree-structures/r-tree] When a data object is fully contained in a single rectangle, the choice is clear.
[src:index-tree-structures/r-tree] When there are multiple options or rectangles in need of enlargement, the choice can have a significant impact on the performance of the tree.
[src:index-tree-structures/r-tree] The objects are inserted into the subtree that needs the least enlargement.
[src:index-tree-structures/r-tree] A Mixture heuristic is employed throughout.
[src:index-tree-structures/r-tree] What happens next is it tries to minimize the overlap (in case of ties, prefer least enlargement and then least area); at the higher levels, it behaves similar to the R-tree, but on ties again preferring the subtree with smaller area.
[src:index-tree-structures/r-tree] The decreased overlap of rectangles in the R*-tree is one of the key benefits over the traditional R-tree.
[src:index-tree-structures/r-tree] Since redistributing all objects of a node into two nodes has an exponential number of options, a heuristic needs to be employed to find the best split.
[src:index-tree-structures/r-tree] In the classic R-tree, Guttman proposed two such heuristics, called QuadraticSplit and LinearSplit.
[src:index-tree-structures/r-tree] In quadratic split, the algorithm searches for the pair of rectangles that is the worst combination to have in the same node, and puts them as initial objects into the two new groups.
[src:index-tree-structures/r-tree] It then searches for the entry which has the strongest preference for one of the groups (in terms of area increase) and assigns the object to this group until all objects are assigned (satisfying the minimum fill).
[src:index-tree-structures/r-tree] In addition to having a more advanced splitting heuristic, the R*-tree also tries to avoid splitting a node by reinserting some of the node members, which is similar to the way a B-tree balances overflowing nodes.
[src:index-tree-structures/r-tree] This was shown to also reduce overlap and thus increase tree performance.
[src:index-tree-structures/r-tree] Finally, the X-tree can be seen as a R*-tree variant that can also decide to not split a node, but construct a so-called super-node containing all the extra entries, when it doesn't find a good split (in particular for high-dimensional data).
[src:index-tree-structures/r-tree] Deleting an entry from a page may require updating the bounding rectangles of parent pages.
[src:index-tree-structures/r-tree] However, when a page is underfull, it will not be balanced with its neighbors.
[src:index-tree-structures/r-tree] Instead, the page will be dissolved and all its children (which may be subtrees, not only leaf objects) will be reinserted.
[src:index-tree-structures/r-tree] If during this process the root node has a single element, the tree height can decrease.
[src:index-tree-structures/skip-list] In computer science, a **skip list** (or **skiplist**) is a probabilistic data structure that allows ${\mathcal {O}}(\log n)$ average complexity for search as well as ${\mathcal {O}}(\log n)$ average complexity for insertion within an ordered sequence of n elements.
[src:index-tree-structures/skip-list] Thus it can get the best features of a sorted array (for searching) while maintaining a linked list-like structure that allows insertion, which is not possible with a static array.
[src:index-tree-structures/skip-list] Fast search is made possible by maintaining a linked hierarchy of subsequences, with each successive subsequence skipping over fewer elements than the previous one *(see the picture below)*.
[src:index-tree-structures/skip-list] Searching starts in the sparsest subsequence until two consecutive elements have been found, one smaller and one larger than or equal to the element searched for.
[src:index-tree-structures/skip-list] Via the linked hierarchy, these two elements link to elements of the next sparsest subsequence, where searching is continued until finally searching in the full sequence.
[src:index-tree-structures/skip-list] The elements that are skipped over may be chosen probabilistically or deterministically, with the former being more common.
[src:index-tree-structures/skip-list] The bottom layer 1 is an ordinary ordered linked list.
[src:index-tree-structures/skip-list] Each higher layer acts as an "express lane" for the lists below, where an element in layer i appears in layer $i+1$ with some fixed probability p (two commonly used values for p are $1/2$ or $1/4$ ).
[src:index-tree-structures/skip-list] On average, each element appears in $1/(1-p)$ lists, and the tallest element (usually a special head element at the front of the skip list) appears in all the lists.
[src:index-tree-structures/skip-list] The skip list contains $\log _{1/p}n\,$ (i.e. logarithm base $1/p$ of n ) lists.
[src:index-tree-structures/skip-list] A search for a target element begins at the head element in the top list, and proceeds horizontally until the current element is greater than or equal to the target.
[src:index-tree-structures/skip-list] If the current element is equal to the target, it has been found.
[src:index-tree-structures/skip-list] If the current element is greater than the target, or the search reaches the end of the linked list, the procedure is repeated after returning to the previous element and dropping down vertically to the next lower list.
[src:index-tree-structures/skip-list] The expected number of steps in each linked list is at most $1/p$ , which can be seen by tracing the search path backwards from the target until reaching an element that appears in the next higher list or reaching the beginning of the current list.
[src:index-tree-structures/skip-list] Therefore, the total *expected* cost of a search is ${\tfrac {1}{p}}\log _{1/p}n$ which is ${\mathcal {O}}(\log n)\,$ , when p is a constant.
[src:index-tree-structures/skip-list] By choosing different values of p , it is possible to trade search costs against storage costs.
[src:index-tree-structures/skip-list] For example, the value $p=1/e$ minimizes the average search time of skip lists, whereas the value $p=1/2$ simplifies their implementation.
[src:index-tree-structures/skip-list] The elements used for a skip list can contain more than one pointer since they can participate in more than one list.
[src:index-tree-structures/skip-list] Insertions and deletions are implemented much like the corresponding linked-list operations, except that "tall" elements must be inserted into or deleted from more than one linked list.
[src:index-tree-structures/skip-list] (Choose the level of the i'th finite node to be 1 plus the number of times it is possible to repeatedly divide i by 2 before it becomes odd.
[src:index-tree-structures/skip-list] Also, i=0 for the negative infinity header as there is the usual special case of choosing the highest possible level for negative and/or positive infinite nodes.) However this also allows someone to know where all of the higher-than-level 1 nodes are and delete them.
[src:index-tree-structures/skip-list] Like the derandomized version, quasi-randomization is only done when there is some other reason to be running an ${\mathcal {O}}(n)$ operation (which visits every node).
[src:index-tree-structures/skip-list] The advantage of this quasi-randomness is that it doesn't give away nearly as much level-structure related information to an adversarial user as the de-randomized one.
[src:index-tree-structures/skip-list] This is desirable because an adversarial user who is able to tell which nodes are not at the lowest level can pessimize performance by simply deleting higher-level nodes.
[src:index-tree-structures/skip-list] (Bethea and Reiter however argue that nonetheless an adversary can use probabilistic and timing methods to force performance degradation.) The search performance is still guaranteed to be logarithmic.
[src:index-tree-structures/skip-list] It would be tempting to make the following "optimization": In the part which says "Next, for each *i*th...", forget about doing a coin-flip for each even-odd pair.
[src:index-tree-structures/skip-list] Just flip a coin once to decide whether to promote only the even ones or only the odd ones.
[src:index-tree-structures/skip-list] Instead of ${\mathcal {O}}(n\log n)$ coin flips, there would only be ${\mathcal {O}}(\log n)$ of them.
[src:index-tree-structures/skip-list] Unfortunately, this gives the adversarial user a 50/50 chance of being correct upon guessing that all of the even numbered nodes (among the ones at level 1 or higher) are higher than level one.
[src:index-tree-structures/skip-list] This is despite the property that there is a very low probability of guessing that a particular node is at level *N* for some integer *N*.
[src:index-tree-structures/skip-list] A skip list does not provide the same absolute worst-case performance guarantees as more traditional balanced tree data structures, because it is always possible (though with very low probability) that the coin-flips used to build the skip list will produce a badly balanced structure.
[src:index-tree-structures/skip-list] However, they work well in practice, and the randomized balancing scheme has been argued to be easier to implement than the deterministic balancing schemes used in balanced binary search trees.
[src:index-tree-structures/skip-list] Skip lists are also useful in parallel computing, where insertions can be done in different parts of the skip list in parallel without any global rebalancing of the data structure.
[src:index-tree-structures/skip-list] Such parallelism can be especially advantageous for resource discovery in an ad-hoc wireless network because a randomized skip list can be made robust to the loss of any single node.
[src:index-tree-structures/skip-list] For every link, also store the width of the link.
[src:index-tree-structures/skip-list] The width is defined as the number of bottom layer links being traversed by each of the higher layer "express lane" links.
[src:index-tree-structures/skip-list] Notice that the width of a higher level link is the sum of the component links below it (i.e. the width 10 link spans the links of widths 3, 2 and 5 immediately below it).
[src:index-tree-structures/skip-list] Consequently, the sum of all widths is the same on every level (10 + 1 = 1 + 3 + 2 + 5 = 1 + 2 + 1 + 2 + 3 + 2).
[src:index-tree-structures/skip-list] To index the skip list and find the i'th value, traverse the skip list while counting down the widths of each traversed link.
[src:index-tree-structures/skip-list] Descend a level whenever the upcoming width would be too large.
[src:index-tree-structures/skip-list] For example, to find the node in the fifth position (Node 5), traverse a link of width 1 at the top level.
[src:index-tree-structures/skip-list] Now four more steps are needed but the next width on this level is ten which is too large, so drop one level.
[src:index-tree-structures/skip-list] Since another step of width 2 would be too far, drop down to the bottom level.
[src:index-tree-structures/skip-list] Now traverse the final link of width 1 to reach the target running total of 5 (1+3+1).
[src:index-tree-structures/skip-list] Skip lists were first described in 1989 by William Pugh.
[src:index-tree-structures/skip-list] There are also several US patents for using skip lists to implement (lockless) priority queues and concurrent dictionaries.
[src:index-tree-structures/trie] In computer science, a **trie** (/ˈtraɪ/, /ˈtriː/ ⓘ), also known as a **digital tree** or **prefix tree**, is a specialized search tree data structure used to store and retrieve strings from a dictionary or set.
[src:index-tree-structures/trie] Unlike a binary search tree, nodes in a trie do not store their associated key.
[src:index-tree-structures/trie] Instead, each node's *position* within the trie determines its associated key, with the connections between nodes defined by individual characters rather than the entire key.
[src:index-tree-structures/trie] Tries are particularly effective for tasks such as autocomplete, spell checking, and IP routing, offering advantages over hash tables due to their prefix-based organization and lack of hash collisions.
[src:index-tree-structures/trie] Every child node shares a common prefix with its parent node, and the root node represents the empty string.
[src:index-tree-structures/trie] While basic trie implementations can be memory-intensive, various optimization techniques such as compression and bitwise representations have been developed to improve their efficiency.
[src:index-tree-structures/trie] A notable optimization is the radix tree, which provides more efficient prefix-based storage.
[src:index-tree-structures/trie] While tries store character strings, they can be adapted to work with any ordered sequence of elements, such as permutations of digits or shapes.
[src:index-tree-structures/trie] A notable variant is the **bitwise trie**, which uses individual bits from fixed-length binary data (such as integers or memory addresses) as keys.
[src:index-tree-structures/trie] The idea of a trie for representing a set of strings was first abstractly described by Axel Thue in 1912.
[src:index-tree-structures/trie] Tries were first described in a computer context by René de la Briandais in 1959.
[src:index-tree-structures/trie] The idea was independently described in 1960 by Edward Fredkin, who coined the term *trie*, pronouncing it /ˈtriː/ (as "tree"), after the middle syllable of *retrieval*.
[src:index-tree-structures/trie] However, other authors pronounce it /ˈtraɪ/ (as "try"), in an attempt to distinguish it verbally from "tree".
[src:index-tree-structures/trie] Tries are a form of string-indexed look-up data structure, which is used to store a dictionary list of words that can be searched on in a manner that allows for efficient generation of completion lists.
[src:index-tree-structures/trie] A prefix trie is an ordered tree data structure used in the representation of a set of strings over a finite alphabet set, which allows efficient storage of words with common prefixes.
[src:index-tree-structures/trie] Tries can be efficacious on string-searching algorithms such as predictive text, approximate string matching, and spell checking in comparison to binary search trees.
[src:index-tree-structures/trie] A trie can be seen as a tree-shaped deterministic finite automaton.
[src:index-tree-structures/trie] Tries support various operations: insertion, deletion, and lookup of a string key.
[src:index-tree-structures/trie] Tries are composed of nodes that contain links, which either point to other suffix child nodes or *null*.
[src:index-tree-structures/trie] As for every tree, each node except the root is pointed to by only one other node, called its *parent*.
[src:index-tree-structures/trie] Each node contains as many links as the number of characters in the applicable alphabet (although tries tend to have a substantial number of null links).
[src:index-tree-structures/trie] In some cases, the alphabet used is simply that of the character encoding—resulting in, for example, a size of 128 in the case of ASCII.
[src:index-tree-structures/trie] Each node contains one possible link to a prefix of strong keys of the set.
[src:index-tree-structures/trie] A basic structure type of nodes in the trie is as follows: ${\text{Node}}$ may contain an optional ${\text{Value}}$ , which is associated with the key that corresponds to the node.
[src:index-tree-structures/trie] Searching for a value in a trie is guided by the characters in the search string key, as each node in the trie contains a corresponding link to each possible character in the given string.
[src:index-tree-structures/trie] Thus, following the string within the trie yields the associated value for the given string key.
[src:index-tree-structures/trie] A null link during the search indicates the inexistence of the key.
[src:index-tree-structures/trie] The following pseudocode implements the search procedure for a given string key in a rooted trie x.
[src:index-tree-structures/trie] In the above pseudocode, x and key correspond to the pointer of the trie's root node and the string key, respectively.
[src:index-tree-structures/trie] The search operation takes $O(m)$ time, where m is the size of the string parameter key.
[src:index-tree-structures/trie] In a balanced binary search tree, on the other hand, it takes $O(m\log n)$ time, in the worst case, since key needs to be compared with $O(\log n)$ other keys and each comparison takes $O(m)$ time, in the worst case.
[src:index-tree-structures/trie] The trie occupies less space, in comparison with a binary search tree, in the case of a large number of short strings, since nodes share common initial string subsequences and store the keys implicitly.
[src:index-tree-structures/trie] Insertion into a trie is guided by using the character sets as indexes to the children array until the last character of the string key is reached.
[src:index-tree-structures/trie] Each node in the trie corresponds to one call of the radix sorting routine, as the trie structure reflects the execution pattern of the top-down radix sort.
[src:index-tree-structures/trie] If null links are encountered before reaching the last character of the string key, new nodes are created.
[src:index-tree-structures/trie] The input value is assigned to the value of the last node traversed, which is the node that corresponds to the key.
[src:index-tree-structures/trie] Deletion of a key–value pair from a trie involves finding the node corresponding to the key, setting its value to null, and recursively removing nodes that have no children.
[src:index-tree-structures/trie] The procedure begins by examining key; an empty string indicates arrival at the node corresponding to the (original) key, in which case its value is set to null.
[src:index-tree-structures/trie] If the node, then, has null value and no children, it is removed from the trie by returning null; otherwise, the node is kept by returning the node itself.
[src:index-tree-structures/trie] However, tries are less efficient than a hash table when the data is directly accessed on a secondary storage device such as a hard disk drive that has higher random access time than the main memory.
[src:index-tree-structures/trie] Tries can be represented in several ways, corresponding to different trade-offs between memory use and speed of the operations.
[src:index-tree-structures/trie] Using a vector of pointers for representing a trie consumes enormous space; however, memory space can be reduced at the expense of running time if a singly linked list is used for each node vector, as most entries of the vector contains ${\text{nil}}$ .
[src:index-tree-structures/trie] Techniques such as *alphabet reduction* may reduce the large space requirements by reinterpreting the original string as a longer string over a smaller alphabet.
[src:index-tree-structures/trie] For example, a string of n bytes can alternatively be regarded as a string of 2*n* four-bit units.
[src:index-tree-structures/trie] This can reduce memory usage by a factor of eight; but lookups need to visit twice as many nodes in the worst case.
[src:index-tree-structures/trie] Another technique includes storing a vector of 256 ASCII pointers as a bitmap of 256 bits representing ASCII alphabet, which reduces the size of individual nodes dramatically.
[src:index-tree-structures/trie] Bitwise tries are used to address the enormous space requirement for the trie nodes in a naive simple pointer vector implementations.
[src:index-tree-structures/trie] Each character in the string key set is represented via individual bits, which are used to traverse the trie over a string key.
[src:index-tree-structures/trie] The implementations for these types of trie use vectorized CPU instructions to find the first set bit in a fixed-length key input (e.g.
[src:index-tree-structures/trie] GCC's `__builtin_clz()` intrinsic function).
[src:index-tree-structures/trie] Accordingly, the set bit is used to index the first item, or child node, in the 32- or 64-entry based bitwise tree.
[src:index-tree-structures/trie] Search then proceeds by testing each subsequent bit in the key.
[src:index-tree-structures/trie] This procedure is also cache-local and highly parallelizable due to register independency, and thus performant on out-of-order execution CPUs.
[src:index-tree-structures/trie] Radix tree, also known as a **compressed trie**, is a space-optimized variant of a trie in which any node with only one child gets merged with its parent; elimination of branches of the nodes with a single child results in better metrics in both space and time.
[src:index-tree-structures/trie] This works best when the trie remains static and set of keys stored are very sparse within their representation space.
[src:index-tree-structures/trie] One more approach for static tries is to "pack" the trie by storing disjoint sets of children in the same memory location, interleaved.
[src:index-tree-structures/trie] Patricia trees are a particular implementation of the compressed binary trie that uses the binary encoding of the string keys in its representation.
[src:index-tree-structures/trie] Every node in a Patricia tree contains an index, known as a "skip number", that stores the node's branching index to avoid empty subtrees during traversal.
[src:index-tree-structures/trie] A naive implementation of a trie consumes immense storage due to larger number of leaf-nodes caused by the sparse distribution of keys; Patricia trees can be efficient for such cases.
[src:index-tree-structures/trie] A representation of a Patricia tree is shown to the right.
[src:index-tree-structures/trie] Each index value adjacent to the nodes represents the "skip number"—the index of the bit with which branching is to be decided.
[src:index-tree-structures/trie] The skip number 1 at node 0 corresponds to the position 1 in the binary encoded ASCII where the leftmost bit differed in the key set X.
[src:index-tree-structures/trie] The skip number is crucial for search, insertion, and deletion of nodes in the Patricia tree, and a bit masking operation is performed during every iteration.
[src:index-tree-structures/trie] Trie data structures are commonly used in predictive text or autocomplete dictionaries, and approximate matching algorithms.
[src:index-tree-structures/trie] Tries enable faster searches, occupy less space, especially when the set contains large number of short strings, thus used in spell checking, hyphenation applications and longest prefix match algorithms.
[src:index-tree-structures/trie] However, if storing dictionary words is all that is required (i.e. there is no need to store metadata associated with each word), a minimal deterministic acyclic finite state automaton (DAFSA) or radix tree would use less storage space than a trie.
[src:index-tree-structures/trie] This is because DAFSAs and radix trees can compress identical branches from the trie that correspond to the same suffixes (or parts) of different words being stored.
[src:index-tree-structures/trie] String dictionaries are also utilized in natural language processing, such as finding lexicon of a text corpus.
[src:index-tree-structures/trie] Lexicographic sorting of a set of string keys can be implemented by building a trie for the given keys and traversing the tree in pre-order fashion; this is also a form of radix sort.
[src:index-tree-structures/trie] Tries are also fundamental data structures for burstsort, which is notable for being the fastest string sorting algorithm as of 2007, accomplished by its efficient use of CPU cache.
[src:index-tree-structures/trie] A special kind of trie, called a suffix tree, can be used to index all suffixes in a text to carry out fast full-text searches.
[src:index-tree-structures/trie] A specialized kind of trie called a compressed trie, is used in web search engines for storing the indexes - a collection of all searchable words.
[src:index-tree-structures/trie] Each terminal node is associated with a list of URLs—called occurrence list—to pages that match the keyword.
[src:index-tree-structures/trie] The trie is stored in the main memory, whereas the occurrence is kept in an external storage, frequently in large clusters, or the in-memory index points to documents stored in an external location.
[src:index-tree-structures/trie] Tries are used in Bioinformatics, notably in sequence alignment software applications such as BLAST, which indexes all the different substrings of length *k* (called k-mers) of a text by storing the positions of their occurrences in a compressed trie sequence databases.
[src:index-tree-structures/trie] Compressed variants of tries, such as databases for managing Forwarding Information Base (FIB), are used in storing IP address prefixes within routers and bridges for prefix-based lookup to resolve mask-based operations in IP routing.
